y Japan and eighteenth-century Tibet to contemporary America, Thailand, and Africa, The Sacred Gaze discusses the religious functions of images and the tools viewers use to interpret them. Morgan questions how fear and disgust of images relate to one another and explains how scholars study the long and evolving histories of images as they pass from culture to culture. An intriguing strand of the narrative details how images have helped to shape popular conceptions of gender and masculinity. The opening chapter considers definitions of "visual culture" and how these relate to the traditional practice of art history. Amply illustrated with more than seventy images from diverse religious traditions, this masterful interdisciplinary study provides a comprehensive and accessible resource for everyone interested in how religious images and visual practice order space and time, communicate with the transcendent, and embody forms of communion with the divine. The Sacred Gaze is a vital introduction to the study of the visual culture of religions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh  aafrica.  aamerica.  achristianity.  acomparative religion.  acontemporary.  across cultural.  adivine communion.  agender and masculinity.  ahistorical review.  aintellectual experiences.  ajapan.  anonfiction.  aperception.  apractical analysis.  areligious imagery.  areligious scholars.  areligious studies.  areligious traditions.  areligious visual culture.  asacred gaze.  asense making.  asocial experience.  aspiritual significance.  athailand.  atheoretical perspective.  atibet.  atranscendence.  avisual culture.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz9780520